 roof","Between the soft palate and nasopharynx"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epalatine tonsils are located between the palatoglossal and palatopharyngeal arches\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as the anterior and posterior tonsillar pillars) in the lateral wall of the oropharynx. This location allows them to effectively sample potential pathogens entering through the mouth and nose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBehind the posterior pharyngeal wall\u003C/strong\u003E - The tonsils are in the lateral walls, not the posterior wall\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithin the posterior third of the tongue\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the location of the lingual tonsils\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithin the nasal cavity roof\u003C/strong\u003E - No lymphoid tissue is normally present in this location\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBetween the soft palate and nasopharynx\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the location of the adenoids (pharyngeal tonsils), not the palatine tonsils\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe palatine tonsils receive blood supply from the tonsillar branch of the facial artery, ascending pharyngeal artery, and ascending palatine artery, all branches of the external carotid artery. They form part of Waldeyer\u0027s ring, an important component of the mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The palatine tonsils are located between the palatoglossal and palatopharyngeal arches in the lateral wall of the oropharynx.","The palatine tonsils contain lymphoid tissue that helps protect against pathogens entering through the mouth and nose.","The palatine tonsils receive blood supply from branches of the external carotid artery including the tonsillar, ascending pharyngeal, and ascending palatine arteries.","The palatine tonsils are also known as \u0022true tonsils\u0022"],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","Dalley AF, Agur AMR. Moore\u2019s Clinically Oriented Anatomy. International edition. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2022.","Drake R. Gray\u2019s Atlas of Anatomy. 3rd ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55474"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17343"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55474"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T05:12:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T05:14:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10033"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70014"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"he